    {
      "question": "In an AP, the sum of first $p$ terms is $q$ and the sum of first $q$ terms is $p$. Show that the sum of first $(p+q)$ terms is $-(p+q)$.",
      "answer": "$S_{p+q} = -(p+q)$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Write sum formulas: $S_p = \\frac{p}{2}[2a + (p-1)d] = q$ and $S_q = \\frac{q}{2}[2a + (q-1)d] = p$.",
          "Simplify to $2a + (p-1)d = \\frac{2q}{p}$ and $2a + (q-1)d = \\frac{2p}{q}$.",
          "Subtract equations to find $d$: $(p-q)d = \\frac{2q}{p} - \\frac{2p}{q} = \\frac{2(q^2 - p^2)}{pq} = \\frac{-2(p-q)(p+q)}{pq}$.",
          "Thus $d = \\frac{-2(p+q)}{pq}$.",
          "Find $2a$ and then $S_{p+q} = \\frac{p+q}{2}[2a + (p+q-1)d]$."
        ],
        "derivation": "Subtracting gives $d = -2/pq(p+q)$. Substituting $d$ back gives $2a = 2/p(q) - (p-1)d$. Sum $S_{p+q} = \\frac{p+q}{2}[2a + (p+q-1)d] = -(p+q)$."
      },
